From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VyOS LS1046A CI <ci@vyos-ls1046a>
Date: Thu, 29 May 2026 05:45:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa1: M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 3 GATE - XSK FILL-ring
 double-release guard audit (xsk_fill_guard_block counter)

M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 3 will perform the hardware-risky true-ZC RX
WRITE: reprogram the FMan RX port primary BPID to the XSK pool's BPID
(MURAM write) and recover the xdp_buff via xsk_buff_recv() in
rx_default_dqrr(). Spec sec 6.1.8 records three DUT crashes from
under-load XSK RX work; the root cause (sec 6.1.8 line ~715) was a
FILL-ring producer outrunning the consumer so the SAME UMEM chunk was
handed to xp_alloc() twice -> xsk_buff_pool free-list (list_head)
corruption -> dcache_clean_poc() paging fault -> softirq panic.

0084's af_xdp_pool_napi_refill() v3 changelog (BMAN HW CONTRACT (c),
spec sec 6.1.8) explicitly documents that "the driver cannot detect a
userspace duplicate" -- it relies entirely on xsk_buff_alloc_batch()
honouring the SPSC contract. That is acceptable for the COPY-mode RX
datapath that ships today (0089), where a duplicated chunk at worst
costs an IVCI on the second bman_release(). It is NOT acceptable as a
precondition for sub-increment 3: once FMan DMAs DIRECTLY into XSK pool
chunks, a duplicate chunk in the BMan pool means FMan can write a frame
into a chunk userspace still believes is free -> the exact in-flight
overwrite sec 6.1.8 line ~80 (0084 contract (c)) warns about, now at
hardware DMA speed instead of a userspace recycle bug.

This patch is the GATE for sub-increment 3, mirroring the strict
observe/assert-before-write cadence (0083 before 0084; 0093/0094 before
the reprogram WRITE). It adds an in-driver assertion of the FILL-ring
single-producer invariant: detect a duplicate DMA address WITHIN a
single xsk_buff_alloc_batch() round, and if found, BLOCK the whole
round's bman_release() (bump a counter, log ratelimited, refill cleanly
next NAPI) rather than depositing the duplicate into BMan. NO datapath
change on the shipping path: on default/vpp with no XSK pool bound,
af_xdp_pool_napi_refill() walks zero qbands and the new code is never
reached; even with a pool bound, xsk_buff_alloc_batch() honouring SPSC
means no duplicate is ever seen and the guard counter stays 0 -- the
release path is byte-identical to 0084 v3.

Two additive, datapath-neutral edits:

  - dpaa_eth.h: u64 xsk_fill_guard_block; appended to the contiguous
    xsk_* counter block (after xsk_zc_rx_armed from 0094). 19th xsk_*
    counter.

  - dpaa_ethtool.c: "xsk_fill_guard_block" appended to dpaa_stats_xsk[]
    (length-driven value-emit loop; no loop edit).

  - af_xdp_pool_main.c: inside af_xdp_pool_napi_refill(), after the
    per-handle dma is computed, scan the bmbs[] entries already filled
    in THIS round for the same 64-bit DMA address. On a hit, set a
    per-round `dup` flag, bump priv->xsk_fill_guard_block, and emit a
    dev_warn_ratelimited(). When `dup` is set, the round's chunked
    bman_release() is skipped entirely -- the freed-twice chunk(s) are
    not deposited into BMan, breaking the double-release at the driver
    boundary. The FILL ring refills on the next NAPI tail.

Why block the whole round rather than just the duplicate: the duplicate
is proof the SPSC cursor is already inconsistent for this fill cycle, so
the OTHER addresses in the same batch are no longer trustworthy either
(a corrupted producer cursor can return arbitrary stale handles). The
conservative, crash-proof action is to drop the entire batch and let
the next clean alloc cycle repopulate -- the same "drop > corrupt"
principle the spec sec 6.1.8 probe fix (skipped_recycle) applies on the
userspace side, now enforced in-driver.

What this is NOT: it is not the duplicate-detection that belongs in the
xsk_buff core (0084 contract (c) is correct that the SPSC contract makes
duplicates a userspace/core bug, not a driver bug). It is a defensive
DUT-safety assertion specific to the LS1046A true-ZC path, because here
a duplicate escalates from "drop a packet" to "FMan DMA overwrite of a
live chunk". A non-zero xsk_fill_guard_block on a DUT run is a red flag
that the FILL-ring producer is misbehaving and sub-increment 3 must NOT
be enabled until it is root-caused -- exactly the audit signal this gate
exists to provide.

Spec sec 6.1.8 item 5 (FILL-ring-empty guard) + sec 6.1.12.

Signed-off-by: VyOS LS1046A CI <ci@vyos-ls1046a>
---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -244,6 +244,7 @@ static void af_xdp_pool_napi_refill(struct dpaa_priv *priv)
 struct bm_buffer bmbs[32];
 struct xsk_buff_pool *pool;
 struct bman_pool *bpool;
+bool dup;
 u32 n, i;
 u16 q;
 
@@ -266,15 +267,40 @@ static void af_xdp_pool_napi_refill(struct dpaa_priv *priv)
 continue;
 
 n = xsk_buff_alloc_batch(pool, handles, ARRAY_SIZE(handles));
+dup = false;
 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
+dma_addr_t dma = xsk_buff_xdp_get_dma(handles[i]);
+u32 j;
+
+/* M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 3 GATE (patch 0095): FILL-ring
+ * double-release guard. Scan the addresses already filled in
+ * THIS batch for the same 64-bit DMA cookie. A duplicate means
+ * the XSK FILL ring's single-producer cursor is inconsistent
+ * for this fill cycle (spec sec 6.1.8 root cause): the same
+ * UMEM chunk was deposited twice. Releasing it into BMan twice
+ * is a double-free that, once sub-increment 3 makes FMan DMA
+ * directly into XSK chunks, lets FMan overwrite a chunk
+ * userspace still believes is free. Block the whole round
+ * (drop > corrupt) and let the next NAPI tail refill cleanly.
+ */
+for (j = 0; j < i; j++) {
+if (bm_buffer_get64(&bmbs[j]) == (u64)dma) {
+dup = true;
+break;
+}
+}
 /* Zero bmbs[i].data first; see attach-time seed loop comment.
  * Patch 0087.
  */
 bmbs[i].data = 0;
-bm_buffer_set64(&bmbs[i], xsk_buff_xdp_get_dma(handles[i]));
+bm_buffer_set64(&bmbs[i], dma);
+if (dup)
+break;
 }
-if (n) {
+if (dup) {
+priv->xsk_fill_guard_block++;
+dev_warn_ratelimited(priv->net_dev->dev.parent,
+ "af_xdp_pool: qband %u FILL-ring duplicate chunk detected; round dropped (xsk_fill_guard_block), sub-increment-3 reprogram must stay disabled\n",
+ q);
+} else if (n) {
 /* Chunk bman_release() in 8-buffer batches; HW BUFCOUNT field is
  * 4 bits and rejects num > 8 as Invalid Command Verb. XSK-side
  * counter still bumps once per non-empty alloc batch. Mirror of
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_eth.h
@@ -321,6 +321,23 @@
  */
 u64 xsk_zc_rx_armed;
 
+/* M3-3 step 7 sub-increment 3 GATE (patch 0095): in-driver
+ * assertion of the XSK FILL-ring single-producer invariant.
+ * Bumped (and the whole refill round dropped) by
+ * af_xdp_pool_napi_refill() when a duplicate DMA cookie is seen
+ * within one xsk_buff_alloc_batch() round -- i.e. the FILL ring
+ * deposited the same UMEM chunk twice (spec sec 6.1.8 root
+ * cause). Strictly diagnostic + crash-defensive: it never fires
+ * under a correct SPSC producer, so the bman_release() path is
+ * byte-identical to 0084 v3 on the shipping copy-mode RX path.
+ * A non-zero value is the audit red-flag that gates true-ZC RX
+ * sub-increment 3 (the FMan-port-BPID MURAM reprogram WRITE +
+ * xsk_buff_recv() recover): a misbehaving FILL producer escalates
+ * from a dropped packet to an FMan DMA overwrite of a live chunk,
+ * so the reprogram must stay disabled until this stays 0 under
+ * load. Unreached on default/vpp (no XDP_ZEROCOPY bind).
+ * Spec sec 6.1.8 item 5 + sec 6.1.12.
+ */
+u64 xsk_fill_guard_block;
+
 /* M3-3b (patch 0086): FMan PCD capability bitmask snapshot taken
  * at probe via dpaa_fman_get_caps(). 0 on mainline ucode 106 ->
  * all fman_cc_tree_/fman_hm_/fman_pol_ helpers short-circuit
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_ethtool.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/dpaa_ethtool.c
@@ -73,6 +73,7 @@
 "xsk_tx_conf_zc",
 "xsk_zc_eligible",
 "xsk_zc_rx_armed",
+"xsk_fill_guard_block",
 };
 
 /* HW-offload (PCD-cap) counters (M3-3b / patch 0086). Order MUST match